                     <interp inst="def1-1065-18370403" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">WILLIAM HUTCHINSON</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18370403-1065-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18370403-1065-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18370403-1065-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="pocketpicking"></interp>for stealing, on the <rs id="t18370403-cd-125" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18370403-1065-offence-1 t18370403-cd-125"></join>21st of March</rs>, 1 handkerchief, value 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., the goods of <persName id="t18370403-name-943" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18370403-name-943" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18370403-name-943" type="surname" value="BATLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18370403-name-943" type="given" value="ELIJAH"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18370403-1065-offence-1 t18370403-name-943"></join>Elijah Batley</persName>, from his person.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18370403-name-944" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18370403-name-944" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18370403-name-944" type="surname" value="BATLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18370403-name-944" type="given" value="ELIJAH"></interp>ELIJAH BATLEY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am an officer of the Customs, and live in Crown<lb></lb>place, Mile-end-road. I was in the Commercial-road on the afternoon of the 21st of March, and felt a twitch behind me—I turned round, and caught the prisoner about a yard from me, in the act of putting my handkerchief into his trowsers pocket—I secured him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner.</hi> Two boys took it and I ran up to the gentleman, and tapped him on the shoulder. <hi rend="italic">Witness.</hi> He did not—I took it out of his pocket—there was only one person passing at the time, and no boys near him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18370403-name-945" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18370403-name-945" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18370403-name-945" type="surname" value="HOGSDEN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18370403-name-945" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE HOGSDEN</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-sergeant K</hi> 122.) The prisoner was given in my charge by the prosecutor for stealing his handkerchief—he denied it—</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183704030166"></xptr>
               <p>but in going to the office he told me he had taken it, and if I would let him go he would never do it again.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner.</hi> It is false—I said I did not do it—it is a thing I was not brought up to—two boys threw it down, I took it up, and said, "Here is your handkerchief"—I only asked him to go to my parents. <hi rend="italic">Witness.</hi> He did not, he wished me to go and inform his parents, and When I went to them they disowned him—I did not find them by his directions.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">
                     <rs id="t18370403-1065-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
